snippet.textDisplay: "I think that we've become very disconnected from the natural world, and many of us, what we're guilty of is an egocentric worldview — the belief that we're the center of the universe. We go into the natural world, and we plunder it for its resources. We feel entitled to artificially inseminate a cow, and when she gives birth, we steal her baby, even though her cries of anguish are unmistakable. Then, we take her milk, that's intended for her calf, and we put it in our coffee and our cereal, and I think we fear the idea of personal change because we think that we have to sacrifice something to give something up. But human beings, at our best, are so inventive and creative and ingenious, and I think that when we use love and compassion as our guiding principles, we can create, develop and implement systems of change that are beneficial to all sentient beings and to the environment": WELL SAID!

snippet.textDisplay:
He delivered a sincere and powerful message for change, for personal change. How many of you will even consider personal change? Social change begins with personal change! Here's a further thought to his message:


Native American relationship to animals: THERE IS NO SENSE IN NATIVE AMERICAN CULTURES THAT THEY ARE "INFERIOR" BEINGS TO HUMANS. An American Indian philosopher said that the "European ideology of human superiority" to animals--ingrained in the Law, Religion, Commerce, and Lifestyle of the Dominant Culture--is destroying the "animal nations." Ideas of human "superiority" to other animals are impossible to prove, he said, although history indicates that they are quite easily rationalized. It is a dangerous philosophy because of its logical extensions. "If humans are superior to animals, might not some humans be superior to other humans?" It cannot be proven that one culture is superior to another, anymore than one species can be proved to be superior to another, it can only be rationalized. Such ideas sound strange to a classist society that has been socialized to regard nonhuman life as "alien," "inferior," a mere commodity, and a joke.

snippet.textDisplay: I loved how Joaquin Phoenix acknowledged, with such beautiful humility, the privilege he knows he enjoys. Privilege that is not due to his race or his gender, not even by virtue of his extraordinary talent. It's like Joaquin has had his eyes opened to know he's also been very lucky*. There is often so much high-handedness among the privileged at the Oscars (Spike Lee over the years comes to mind), the privileged who, in Hollywood, come in every shade of race and range of gender, sexual orientations, etc. who get all puffed up with righteousness but who are truly blind to their own entitlement. That is, just how much *luck has come into play in their own success. Maybe Joaquin's work in really getting down deep into his character in "Joker" really and truly opened his eyes to how the vast majority of humans actually live and the everyday struggles with which they contend. And having the blinders torn from his eyes where the suffering of everyday humans is concerned also seems to have opened his heart to the suffering of not only humans, but all other sentient beings on the planet, too. I don't know, but I thought it was beautiful, his speech. Heart WIDE open. Thank you, Joaquin.
